
======================================================================
  PART 1: F(5) = 5 — THE FIBONACCI FIXED POINT
======================================================================

Fibonacci sequence: F(0)=0, F(1)=1, F(n) = F(n-1)+F(n-2)

  F( 0) =    0  ← FIXED POINT
  F( 1) =    1  ← FIXED POINT
  F( 2) =    1
  F( 3) =    2
  F( 4) =    3
  F( 5) =    5  ← FIXED POINT
  F( 6) =    8
  F( 7) =   13
  F( 8) =   21
  F( 9) =   34
  F(10) =   55
  F(11) =   89
  F(12) =  144  ← F(12) = 144

Fixed points of F: {n : F(n) = n}
  F(0) = 0 ✓ (trivial)
  F(1) = 1 ✓ (trivial)
  F(5) = 5 ✓ (NON-TRIVIAL)
  F(12) = 144 ≠ 12

CLAIM: 5 is the ONLY prime fixed point of the Fibonacci sequence.
  (0 and 1 are the only other fixed points.)

PROOF: F(n)/n → φ^{n-1}/√5/n → ∞ as n → ∞
  So F(n) > n for all sufficiently large n.
  Check: F(6)=8>6, F(7)=13>7, ... all subsequent F(n)>n.
  And F(2)=1<2, F(3)=2<3, F(4)=3<4.
  So the ONLY nontrivial fixed point is F(5)=5. QED

This makes 5 SELF-REFERENTIAL in the Fibonacci sequence,
just as 2 is self-referential in the Jacobsthal evaluation x=2.

======================================================================
  PART 2: LUCAS NUMBERS — L(5) = 11
======================================================================

Lucas sequence: L(0)=2, L(1)=1, L(n) = L(n-1)+L(n-2)

  L( 0) =    2  ← KEY NUMBER
  L( 1) =    1
  L( 2) =    3  ← KEY NUMBER
  L( 3) =    4
  L( 4) =    7  ← KEY NUMBER
  L( 5) =   11  ← KEY NUMBER
  L( 6) =   18
  L( 7) =   29
  L( 8) =   47
  L( 9) =   76
  L(10) =  123

REMARKABLE: The Lucas sequence at n=0,1,2,3,4,5 gives:
  L(0) = 2   (first key)
  L(1) = 1   (identity)
  L(2) = 3   (second key)
  L(3) = 4   (= 2²)
  L(4) = 7   (= 2³-1, Mersenne prime, transition)
  L(5) = 11  (decimal pair number!)

So the Lucas sequence GENERATES the hierarchy numbers!
  L(0)=2, L(2)=3, L(4)=7, L(5)=11
  And L is evaluated at 5 to get 11!

The bridge: 5 maps to 11 under the Lucas map.
This is the Q(√5) bridge in disguise!
  L(n) = φ^n + (-1/φ)^n
  L(5) = φ⁵ + (-1/φ)⁵ = φ⁵ - 1/φ⁵
  φ⁵ = 11.090170
  1/φ⁵ = 0.090170
  φ⁵ - 1/φ⁵ = 11.000000
  φ⁵ + (-1/φ)⁵ = 11.000000
  = 11.000000 ✓

Fibonacci-Lucas identities at n=5:
  F(5) = 5 = 5
  L(5) = 11 = 11
  F(5) · L(5) = 5 · 11 = 55 = F(10)
  Check: F(10) = 55 = 55 ✓
  L(5)² - 5·F(5)² = 121 - 125 = -4 = -4·(-1)⁵
  This is the identity L(n)² - 5F(n)² = 4(-1)^n ✓

  F(2·5) = F(5)·L(5) = 5·11 = 55
  This means: 5 and 11 are LINKED via doubling in Fibonacci!
  The (5, 11) pair in the hierarchy corresponds to
  the (n, 2n) doubling in Fibonacci: F(2n) = F(n)·L(n).

