======================================================================
  PART 7: THE 5-10-11 TRIANGLE
======================================================================

Three numbers linked by 5:
  5 = F(5) = L(5)/11 · 5 (Fibonacci fixed point)
  10 = 2·5 = F(5)·L(0) (Fibonacci·Lucas)
  11 = L(5) (Lucas at 5)

The TRIANGLE:
  5 ──(×2)──→ 10 ──(+1)──→ 11
  ↑                            ↑
  F(n=5)                    L(n=5)

In tournament terms:
  5 = bridge modulus (2+3)
  10 = x + x³ = 2 + 8 (digit shift)
  11 = 1 + x + x³ = 1 + 2 + 8 (digit shift + 1)

The Q(√5) field connects all three:
  F(5) = 5, in Q(√5) via Binet: F(n) = (φⁿ-ψⁿ)/√5
  L(5) = 11, in Q(√5) via Lucas: L(n) = φⁿ+ψⁿ
  F(10) = 55 = 5·11 = F(5)·L(5)
  F(5)·L(5) = F(2·5) = F(10)

And the KEY identity: F(n)·L(n) = F(2n)
At n=5: 5·11 = 55 = F(10)
At n=10: F(10)·L(10) = 55·123 = 6765 = F(20)
Check: F(20) = 6765 = correct!
  F(20) = 6765, 55·123 = 6765

THE TOWER:
  F(5) = 5
  F(10) = F(5)·L(5) = 5·11 = 55
  F(20) = F(10)·L(10) = 55·123 = 6765
  Each doubling multiplies by a Lucas number.
  This is the 'doubling formula' for Fibonacci.

======================================================================
  PART 8: SYNTHESIS — EVERYTHING IS RECURRENCES
======================================================================

THE COMPLETE WEB OF RECURRENCES THROUGH 5:

1. FIBONACCI: F(n) = F(n-1) + F(n-2)
   F(5) = 5 (fixed point)
   Discriminant = 5 (creates Q(√5))
   Roots: φ = (1+√5)/2 = 1.618...

2. LUCAS: L(n) = L(n-1) + L(n-2)
   L(5) = 11 (maps 5 to 11)
   Same discriminant, same field Q(√5)
   Product: F(5)·L(5) = F(10) = 55

3. JACOBSTHAL: J(n) = J(n-1) + 2J(n-2)
   J(5) = 11 (ALSO maps to 11!)
   Discriminant = 9 = 3² (RATIONAL)
   Roots: 2, -1

   J(5) = 11 = 11 ✓

AMAZING: Both Lucas AND Jacobsthal map 5 to 11!
  L(5) = 11  (via Fibonacci recurrence with initial (2,1))
  J(5) = 11  (via Jacobsthal recurrence with initial (0,1))

  Lucas uses the x=1 recurrence (Fibonacci world)
  Jacobsthal uses the x=2 recurrence (tournament world)
  BOTH reach 11 at n=5!

This is the DEEPEST bridge:
  5 is where the Fibonacci world (x=1) and
  the tournament world (x=2) AGREE on an output value.
  At n=5: L_fib(5) = J_jac(5) = 11.

4. PENTANACCI: T(n) = T(n-1)+T(n-2)+T(n-3)+T(n-4)+T(n-5)
   Dominant root → 2 (98.3%)
   The '5-step lookback' in the k-nacci

5. Q(√5) TOWER: G₁₁(n) = G(n-1) + 11G(n-2)
   Root = 3φ-1 ≈ 3.854
   G₁₁(n) ≡ F(n) (mod 5)
   Connects x=1 to x=11 via Q(√5)

SUMMARY:
  The number 5 is the UNIQUE fixed point of the Fibonacci map
  among primes. It sits at the intersection of:
    - The Fibonacci recurrence (x=1): F(5) = 5
    - The Jacobsthal recurrence (x=2): J(5) = 11 = L(5)
    - The number field Q(√5) connecting x=1 and x=11
    - The pentanacci getting 98.3% of the way to 2
    - The forbidden residue barrier at n=5
    - The 5-cycle that enables cross-level coupling at n=8

  In the user's words: 5 IS the mortar between 2 and 3.
  Without it, the bricks don't hold together.

Done.
